<SECTION>
<P>
Book Review; Page 36; Book Review Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Immigrants leaving Ellis Island in 1910. After decades of abandonment, 
the famous gateway through which so many immigrants passed into America has 
finally been restored. "Ellis Island: Echoes From a Nation's Past" (Aperture: 
$39.95) accompanies an exhibition that will be mounted in conjunction with the 
monument's opening to visitors next year. The book, edited by Susan Jones, 
includes an extensive history of the Island and a detailed study of its 
architecture, as well as a moving personal essay on the years of neglect by the 
recently-deceased Aperture board chairman Shirley C. Burden. A celebration of 
photography as well as a document of the place, "Ellis Island" contains images 
by such well-known art photographers as Jerry Uelsmann and Emmet Gowin. Filled 
with dozens of family portraits and both historic and contemporary documentary 
photos, the book resists the temptation for superficial flag-waving, instead 
providing a thoughtful and loving portrait of this sacred landmark in the 
American soul. 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
