<P>
A 'REAL' TV WOMAN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
There has been much criticism of the portrayal of women in the new crop of TV 
shows this fall, but there is one show I want to commend. 
</P>
<P>
That show is "Peaceable Kingdom." Somehow, in the midst of America's TV 
wasteland, this show successfully portrays: a woman in a leadership position 
who is competent at both management and parenting; realistic conflict among 
adults; a message of ecological concern and value; real-life child-rearing 
issues that interest kids of nearly all ages; no unrealistic or gratuitous 
violence and sex, just reasonably healthy relationships and normal motivations. 
</P>
<P>
Wher else on the major networks can we find so much to admire -- and enjoy -- 
in one hour? 
</P>
<P>
PAUL M. DU BOIS 
</P>
<P>
San Rafael, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
 "Peaceable Kingdom," which stars Lindsay Wagner as a zoo director, has been 
canceled. It will disappear Dec. 6. 
