<HEADLINE>
<P>
THERE'S GOOD REASON FOR POOR AMERICAN CAR SALES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
I believe your reporter, the market analysts and the auto industry are all 
missing the real reason behind falling sales of American cars ("Rebates, 
Production Cuts Blamed for 27.5% Drop in Auto Profits," Oct. 27). 
</P>
<P>
The real reason for U.S. auto makers' problems is that they are simply losing 
the competition with foreign car makers. 
</P>
<P>
One auto industry expert, Brock Yates, blames management as well as labor in 
his book, "The Decline and Fall of the American Automobile Industry." 
</P>
<P>
American buyers are not as naive as American car makers may think. Getting 
rebates or long warranty periods are meaningless if you have a car that keeps 
needing repair or just doesn't work right. 
</P>
<P>
It would be truly refreshing if American cars actually performed as well as the 
sexy advertisements. 
</P>
<P>
Unless American car makers start making better cars and stop trying to fool 
American car buyers, I think I, for one, will continue to buy foreign cars. 
</P>
<P>
WILLIAM C. PATTERSON, TUSTIN 
</P>
</TEXT>
