<HEADLINE>
<P>
TAGLIABUE TO MEET WITH NFL OWNERS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BOB OATES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Paul Tagliabue, the new NFL commissioner, will hold a three-day series of 
executive sessions with club presidents in Dallas early next month to discuss 
the player-owner impasse and other issues. 
</P>
<P>
Meetings are planned with owners representing two divisions each day on the 
following schedule: 
</P>
<P>
Dec. 5 -- NFC West, AFC East. 
</P>
<P>
Dec. 6 -- Both Central divisions. 
</P>
<P>
Dec. 7 -- NFC East, AFC West. 
</P>
<P>
Raider owner Al Davis and two or three other presidents favor some form of free 
agency. 
</P>
<P>
Other owners have discussed a salary cap combined with a player wage scale. 
</P>
<P>
In former years, NFL meetings have normally involved all 28 clubs. Tagliabue 
said that in sessions with small groups of owners, more of them may feel like 
participating. 
</P>
<P>
"This is an imaginative way to get into some tricky issues," a club executive 
said. "I hope some of the ideas proposed will be equally so." 
</P>
<P>
Other subjects on Tagliabue's agenda are television, international plans and a 
review of NFL office procedures. BOB OATES 
</P>
</TEXT>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
TAGLIABUE, PAUL; COMMISSIONER OF FOOTBALL; TEAM OWNERS; FOOTBALL PLAYERS; FREE 
AGENTS (SPORTS); NATIONAL FOOTBALL LEAGUE 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
