<HEADLINE>
<P>
MISSISSIPPI CAPITALIZES, EARNS LIBERTY BERTH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
JACKSON, Miss. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Liberty Bowl-bound Mississippi knows how to take advantage of the breaks. 
</P>
<P>
As a result, the Rebels earned a 21-11 victory over arch-rival Mississippi 
State Saturday and will carry that momentum into their Dec. 28 bowl game where 
they probably will play Air Force. 
</P>
<P>
"It wasn't one of our better performances. Give Mississippi State a lot of 
credit, they played good, solid football," said Mississippi Coach Billy Brewer, 
who is taking his third Rebel team to a bowl in his seven seasons at his alma 
mater. 
</P>
<P>
"We were patched up and we played hard for 11 games. This is probably as good 
an overall performance by a team that I have coached. To accomplish the seventh 
win today against a solid intrastate rival makes this victory very meaningful." 
</P>
<P>
In a Southeastern Conference defensive struggle before a crowd of 43,218, Ed 
Thigpen and Randy Baldwin scored on one-yard runs and opportunistic Ole Miss 
(7-4) won for the sixth time in the last seven games of the series. 
</P>
<P>
Ending a two-game losing streak, Mississippi, 4-3 in the SEC, used a fumble 
recovery to set up a short second-quarter touchdown drive and then went 93 
yards after a pass interception for one of its two fourth-quarter scores. 
</P>
<P>
Mississippi State (5-6 overall, 1-6 in the SEC), was in the game until a gamble 
backfired late in the third quarter and Ole Miss scored two fourth-quarter 
touchdowns. 
</P>
<P>
Trailing, 7-3, Mississippi State had a fourth down and a yard for a first down 
at the Ole Miss seven, but Todd Jordan's pitch to Jesse Anderson went awry and 
the Bulldogs lost five yards. 
</P>
<P>
The loss was particularly disappointing for Mississippi State, which was 1-10 a 
year ago and had a shot at a bowl game until a loss last week at Louisiana 
State. 
</P>
<P>
"It was a physical game and I think we played really well in some spots," 
Mississippi State Coach Rockey Felker said. "But when we had the opportunities, 
we didn't take advantage of them. 
</P>
<P>
"In particular, the fourth-down call from inside the 10. It seemed after that, 
all the momentum swung over to the Ole Miss side." 
</P>
<P>
Mississippi State hurt itself with turnovers -- losing the ball three times -- 
and had a couple of costly penalties in key situations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
