CALIFORNIA IN BRIEF; 
</P>
<P>
SAN FRANCISCO; 
</P>
<P>
EMBATTLED ATTORNEY WINS U.S. JUDGE SEAT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times staff and wire reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
San Francisco attorney Vaughn R. Walker, whose nomination as a U.S. district 
judge was delayed for two years because of controversy surrounding his 
membership in a club with a record of discrimination, has won Senate 
confirmation. Walker was a 15-year member in the Olympic Club of San Francisco, 
which had no black members until last year and still excludes women. He 
resigned Feb. 15, but critics said the move came too late and questioned his 
claim to have opposed the exclusion of women. 
</P>
